> List,
> This is a silly, lazy question, but -
> Do any of you guys run an old-timey aaooga horn on your bus?
> 
> I have one and can't figure the wiring -mainly because i don't understand the
> horn circuit. The horn looks like this:
> http://cgi.ebay.com/ebaymotors/ws/ebayISAPI.dll?ViewItem&item=1813627103&r=0&t=0
>  but mine is 12v.
> The aooga (actually the 'aooga brand) horn is mounted, uninsulated to the
> front bumper and only has one wire coming out of it.  I figured i needed a

here's where your problem is, the mount is the ground and the wire is +,
the best way to do this is probably to insulate the horn from the body
somehow, disconect it and let it hang free and see if it works.  VW uses
Ground to sound horn so by attaching horn to ground it gets power all the
time.

Bob

> ground wire (since the stock horn appears to use one) and i attached a wire to
> the body of the horn. When i hook both of the wires up to the leads for the
> stock horn and turn the key - the horn is on all the time. This was really
> cool in the inlaw's garage about 2am saturday...
> 
> Anyway - just wondering if anybody else has a bus that sounds as silly as it
> looks and how they wired their horn...
